{{Infobox person
| name          = Ijahnya Christian
| image         = <!-- filename only, no "File:" or "Image:" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->
| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->
| caption       = 
| birth_name    = Carol Patricia Rey
| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|1957}} <!-- {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->
| birth_place   = [[The Valley, Anguilla|The Valley]], [[Saint Christopher-Nevis-Anguilla]], [[British West Indies]]
| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)  -->
| death_place   = 
| nationality   = British
| other_names   = 
| occupation    = social activist and writer
| years_active  = 1980 to present
| known_for     = Pan-Africanism, Rastafari organizing
| notable_works = 
}}

'''Ijahnya Christian''' (born 1957) is an [[Afro-Anguillian]] social activist and noted member of the [[Rastafarian]] community. As a member of the [[pan-African]] and repatriation movements, Christian travels world wide to help preserve the African languages, traditions, and heritage of the [[African diaspora|diaspora]] and encourages study on the history and culture of [[Caribbean]] communities.

==Early life==
Carol Patricia Rey was born in 1957, in [[The Valley, Anguilla|The Valley]] in the [[Saint Christopher-Nevis-Anguilla|British colony of Saint Christopher-Nevis-Anguilla]] to Amethyst and Hugh Rey, a civil servant. Her childhood was spent on each of the three islands of the colony and she graduated from Basseterre High School on [[Saint Kitts|St. Kitts]] in 1976. While she was a teenager, she became interested in the Rastafarian movement, sweeping through the Caribbean after [[Haile Selassie]]'s 1966 visit to the region and [[Bob Marley]]'s music added visibility to the ideology. She joined the movement in 1980, changed her name to Ijahnya Christian, and went on to study social work at the [[University of the West Indies]] in [[Mona, Jamaica]], graduating with a bachelor's degree in 1984.{{sfn|Walicek|2016}} 

==Career==
Returning to Anguilla, Christian began her career as a high school teacher. Simultaneously, she began editing working on two [[Ethnography|ethnographic]] projects. She served as mentor and editor for Lottis Hodge's ''Ning Troubles'' and ''The Dictionary of Anguillian Language''. Lodge's autobiographical work, published in 1988, related the how she overcame the difficulties of her life and the Anguillian Dictionary, published in 1993, was the first work to focus on the linguistic heritage of the island. During the same time frame, Christian was pursuing a master's degree in education at the [[University of Southampton]], in [[Southampton]], England, which she completed in 1991.{{sfn|Walicek|2016}}

Returning to Anguilla, Christian founded the Athlyi Rogers Study Centre. The center, named after the Anguillian writer, [[Robert Athlyi Rogers]] who wrote the ''[[Holy Piby]]'', a text on Rastafari theology, was a [[pan-African]] cultural space. To further her aim of increasing both popular and scholarly attention on Anguillian identity and history, she served as Director of the Department of Youth and Culture from 2004 to 2006. Between 1998 and 2009, she also wrote a regular column for ''The Anguillian'', "Heartically Yours", which discussed cultural and political events on the island.{{sfn|Walicek|2016}}

Christian is a representative for the Caribbean Pan-African Network, speaking on the preservation of language, [[List of Caribbean music genres|Caribbean music]]—including a range from [[Calypso music|Calypso]], [[Chutney Soca]], [[Reggae]] to [[Gospel music|Gospel]]—and heritage.{{sfn|Baldacchino|2011|pp=xxxi, 294}} She was a founding member of the Caribbean Rastafari Organization{{sfn|Walicek|2016}} and became one of the principal organizers of worldwide gatherings of the Rastafari faithful.{{sfn|Edmonds|2012|p=106}} Christian moved to [[Shashamane]], Ethiopia in 2010, to further her work in repatriating the [[African diaspora]] to the mother country, from where she continues her writing and social activism.{{sfn|Walicek|2016}}{{sfn|MacLeod|2014|p=228}} It is her belief that repatriation is protected under the [[United Nations]] principal and laws governing the [[right of return]].{{sfn|MacLeod|2014|p=228}}

