{{Infobox scientist | name = James Fraser Kasting | image = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1953|01|02}} | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | residence = [[United States|U.S.]] | nationality = [[United States]] | field = Geoscience | work_institutions = [[Penn State University]] | alma_mater = [[Harvard University]], [[University of Michigan]] |doctoral_advisor = Tom Donahue<ref name="Quest">{{cite web|title=Jim Kasting|url=http://quest.nasa.gov/people/cfs/specific/CFS-J.Kasting.pdf|website=NASA Quest|accessdate=27 May 2016|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130218231838/http://quest.nasa.gov/people/cfs/specific/CFS-J.Kasting.pdf|archivedate=18 February 2013|df=}}</ref> | awards = | website = http://www.geosc.psu.edu/~kasting/PersonalPage/Kasting.htm }} {{external media | width = 210px | align = right | headerimage= | video1 = [http://www.innovaxiom.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=167932 James Kasting], Origins 2011 congress }}
'''James Fraser Kasting''' (born January 2, 1953) is an American [[Earth science|geoscientist]] and Distinguished Professor of Geosciences at [[Penn State University]]. Kasting is active in NASA’s search for habitable [[Exoplanet|extrasolar planets]].<ref name="Ihrenes"/><ref name="David">{{cite news|last1=David|first1=Leonard|title=How NASA's Kepler Will Seek Out Strange New Worlds|url=http://www.space.com/2270-nasa-kepler-seek-strange-worlds.html|accessdate=27 May 2016|work=[[Space.com]]|date=March 4, 2009}}</ref> He is considered a world leader in the field of [[planetary habitability]], assessing habitable zones around stars.<ref name="Seed">{{cite news|title=Earth-like Planets Aren’t Rare 10 Questions with... Renowned planetary scientist James Kasting on the odds of finding another Earth-like planet and the power of science fiction|url=http://seedmagazine.com/content/article/earth-like_planets_arent_rare/|accessdate=27 May 2016|work=Seed Magazine|date=March 15, 2010}}</ref> He was elected a member of the [[National Academy of Sciences]] in 2018.
==Education== Kasting grew up in [[Huntsville, Alabama]], and credits the nearby [[Marshall Space Flight Center]] and the Mercury, Gemini, and Apollo rockets for inspiring his interests in space and science.<ref name="Seed"/>
Kasting received a A.B. from [[Harvard University]] in 1975. He then went to the [[University of Michigan]], where he worked with Tom Donahue,<ref name="Quest"/> receiving his M.S. in physics and atmospheric science in 1978, and his Ph.D. in [[atmospheric science]] in 1979.<ref name="CV">{{cite web|title=Curriculum Vitae|url=http://www3.geosc.psu.edu/~jfk4/PersonalPage/Kasting.htm|website=Department of Geosciences|quote="Click 'Vitae' to see Dr. Kasting's CV."|accessdate=27 May 2016}}</ref><ref name="Ihrenes">{{cite web|title=ISE - Our Team|url=http://www.ihrenesspaceenterprises.com/james-kasting.php|website=Ihrenes Enterprises|accessdate=27 May 2016}}</ref>
==Research== Kasting worked as a postdoctoral fellow at the National Center for Atmospheric Research and at [[NASA]] [[Ames Research Center]] before accepting a position with the space science division at NASA Ames. He has served NASA in various capacities, including as a member of the scientific working group for the [[Terrestrial Planet Finder]]. Kasting joined [[Penn State University]] in 1988, but continues to collaborate with NASA.<ref name="Quest"/><ref name="Pugh">{{cite news|title=Three Penn State faculty members awarded Evan Pugh Professorships|url=http://news.psu.edu/story/149395/2012/04/26/academics/three-penn-state-faculty-members-awarded-evan-pugh-professorships|accessdate=27 May 2016|work=Penn State News|date=April 26, 2012}}</ref>
He is interested in atmospheric evolution, planetary atmospheres and paleoclimates.<ref name="CV"/> Kasting writes about the [[geophysical]] history and status of the [[Earth]], with a focus on atmospherics. According to Kasting's calculations, the [[Future of the Earth#Loss of oceans|Earth's oceans will evaporate in about a billion years]], while the Sun is still a main sequence star. This date is much earlier than previously thought.<ref name="Carrington">{{cite news|last1=Carrington|first1=Damian|title=Date set for desert Earth|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/sci/tech/specials/washington_2000/649913.stm|accessdate=27 May 2016|work=[[BBC]]|date= February 21, 2000}}</ref> He has also considered the habitability criteria of other [[stellar systems]] and planets. A 1993 paper on [[habitable zone]]s was particularly decisive in shaping thinking on this field.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kasting |first=James F. |author2=Whitmore, Daniel P. |author3=Reynolds, Ray T. |year=1993 |title=Habitable Zones Around Main Sequence Stars |journal=Icarus |format=PDF |issue=1 |pages=108–128 |id= |url=http://www.geosc.psu.edu/~kasting/PersonalPage/Pdf/Icarus_93.pdf |accessdate=2007-08-06 |quote= |doi=10.1006/icar.1993.1010 |volume=101 |bibcode=1993Icar..101..108K |pmid=11536936 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090318115319/http://www.geosc.psu.edu/~kasting/PersonalPage/Pdf/Icarus_93.pdf |archivedate=2009-03-18 |df= }}</ref>
Kasting has published two books, ''The Earth System'',<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kump|first1=Lee R.|last2=Kasting|first2=James F.|last3=Crane|first3=Robert G.|title=The earth system|date=2010|publisher=[[Prentice Hall]]|location=San Francisco|isbn=978-0321597793}}</ref> and ''How to Find a Habitable Planet'',<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kasting|first1=James|title=How to find a habitable planet|date=2010|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]]|location=Princeton, N.J.|isbn=978-0691138053}}</ref> along with more than 140 publications in research journals.<ref name="Ihrenes"/> In their popular 2001 work ''[[Rare Earth hypothesis|Rare Earth:Why Complex Life is Uncommon in the Universe]]'', [[Peter Ward (paleontologist)|Peter Ward]] and Donald Brownlee note: "Although many scientists have been doggedly pursuing the various attributes necessary for a habitable planet...one name stands out in the scientific literature: James Kasting."<ref name=Ward>{{cite book|last1=Ward|first1=Peter D.|last2=Brownlee|first2=Donald|title=Rare earth: Why complex life is uncommon in the universe|date=2004|publisher=Copernicus|location=New York|isbn=9780387952895}}</ref>{{rp|266}}
Kasting is also a member of numerous professional scientific societies and committees. He was elected Fellow of both the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]<ref name=AAAS>{{cite web|title=Book of Members, 1780–2010: Chapter B|url=http://www.amacad.org/publications/BookofMembers/ChapterB.pdf| publisher=[[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] |accessdate=June 3, 2011}}</ref> and [[Geochemical Society]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jim Kasting Elected Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, and of the Geochemical Society|website=NASA Astrobiology Institute|url=https://astrobiology.nasa.gov/news/check-type-jim-kasting-elected-fellow-of-the-american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences-and-of-the-geochemical-society/}}</ref><ref name="GS">{{cite web|title=Geochemical Fellows|url=http://www.geochemsoc.org/awards/geochemicalfellows/|website=Geochemical Society|accessdate=27 May 2016}}</ref> He is also a fellow of the [[American Geophysical Union]] (2004), [[International Society for the Study of the Origin of Life]] (2002), and the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] (1995). He serves on the advisory board of the [[Lifeboat Foundation]].<ref name="Lifeboat">{{cite web|title=Advisory Board|url=http://lifeboat.com/ex/bios.james.f.kasting|website=Lifeboat Foundation|accessdate=27 May 2016}}</ref>
==Awards== He won a [[LExEN|LExEN Award]] for his work "Collaborative Research: Methanogenesis and the Climate of Early Mars".<ref name="NSFLimits">{{cite news|last1=National Science Foundation|title=Limits Of Life On Earth: Are They The Key To Life On Other Planets?|url=http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/1997-10/NSF-LOLO-151097.php|work=EurekaAlert|date=October 15, 1997}}</ref> He won the [[Oparin Medal]], presented by the International Society for the Study of the Origin of Life, in 2008.<ref name="ISSOL">{{cite web|title=Awards and Honors|url=http://issol.org/medals-and-honors/|website=ISSOL|accessdate=27 May 2016}}</ref>
==Personal life== He is married with three children.
