'''Louis Jean Nicolas Abbé''' (28 August 1764 &ndash; 9 April 1834) became a French general during the [[Napoleonic Wars]]. He enlisted as a foot soldier in the royal army in 1784 and was a [[non-commissioned officer]] by 1792. He spent most of the [[French Revolutionary Wars]] fighting in Italy. In 1802 he joined the [[Saint-Domingue expedition]]. He was appointed [[colonel]] in command of the 23rd Light Infantry Regiment in 1803 and led the unit at [[Battle of Caldiero (1805)|Caldiero]], [[Battle of Campo Tenese|Campo Tenese]], [[Battle of Maida|Maida]], and [[Siege of Amantea (1807)|Amantea]]. Promoted to [[general of brigade]] in 1807, he led a brigade in 1809, fighting at [[Battle of Sacile|Sacile]], [[Battle of Caldiero (1809)|Caldiero]], [[Battle of Piave River (1809)|the Piave]], [[Battle of Tarvis (1809)|Tarvis]], [[Battle of Raab|Raab]], and [[Battle of Wagram|Wagram]].

==Recognitions==
[[File:Baron Abbé 3874.jpg|thumb|left|The tomb of General Abbé]]
Starting in 1810, Abbé served in the [[Peninsular War]] in Spain. He fought under Marshal [[Louis Gabriel Suchet]] at [[La Bisbal de Falset|Falset]], [[Siege of Tortosa (1810)|Tortosa]], [[Siege of Tarragona (1811)|Tarragona]], and [[Battle of Montserrat|Montserrat]]. He was promoted to [[general of division]] in 1811. He led a division under Marshal [[Nicolas Soult]] at [[Battle of the Pyrenees|the Pyrenees]], [[Battle of San Marcial|San Marcial]], [[Battle of the Bidassoa (1813)|the Bidassoa]], [[Battle of Nivelle|Nivelle]], [[Battle of the Nive|the Nive]], and [[Battle of Bayonne|Bayonne]]. He joined [[Napoleon]] in 1815 and fought the Austrians before being retired from the army in 1816. He was reactivated from 1830 to 1832 when he retired again. He died in 1834. '''ABBE''' is one of the [[names inscribed under the Arc de Triomphe]], on Column 36.

